{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Cesare Amè | image = Cesare Amè.jpg | imagesize = | caption = Cesare Amè in ''[[Radiocorriere]]'' magazine, 1962. | birth_date = {{birth-date|18 November 1892}} | birth_place = [[Cumiana]], Italy | death_date = {{death-date and age|30 June 1983|18 November 1892}} | death_place = [[Rome]], Italy | death_cause = | birthname = |}} '''Cesare Amè''' (18 November 1892 – 30 June 1983) was an Italian general and intelligence officer.
Born in [[Cumiana]], Amè formed at the [[Modena]] Military School; appointed [[second lieutenant]] in permanent service in 1912, he joined the 92º Regiment of Turin, with whom he tok part to the [[Italo-Turkish War]]. Promoted [[liaison officer]], after the [[World War I]] he was awarded one silver and two bronze medals.<ref name="bio">Giuseppe De Lutiis (1988). "[http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/cesare-ame_(Dizionario-Biografico)/ Amè, Cesare]". ''[[Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani]] - Volume 34''. [[Treccani]].</ref>
In 1921, Amè entered the Italian Military Intelligence Service ([[Servizio Informazioni Militare]], SIM), being promoted to lieutenant colonel in 1927 and to colonel in 1937. He was appointed chief of SIM in 1940; during his service he tried to persuade [[Benito Mussolini]] to not entering war because of the Italian army's lack of preparation, and had to face Mussolini's reticence to disclose his plans.<ref name="bio">Giuseppe De Lutiis (1988). "[http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/cesare-ame_(Dizionario-Biografico)/ Amè, Cesare]". ''[[Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani]] - Volume 34''. [[Treccani]].</ref><ref name="Stampa">{{cite news|title=E' morto Cesare Amè lo 007 di Mussolini|accessdate=|work=[[La Stampa]]|issue=154|date=1 July 1983|page=11}}</ref>
On 18 August 1943, after the fall of Mussolini, Amè was removed from office by [[Pietro Badoglio]] and was assigned to the command of the Italian ary division in [[Ljubljana]]. In 1958 he was appointed [[divisional general]]. He was later author of ''Guerra segreta in Italia'' ("Secret war in Italy", 1956) and of ''Il Servizio informazioni militare dalla sua costituzione alla fine della seconda guerra mondiale'' ("The Military Intelligence Service from its establishment to the end of World War II", released anonymously in 1957).<ref name="bio">Giuseppe De Lutiis (1988). "[http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/cesare-ame_(Dizionario-Biografico)/ Amè, Cesare]". ''[[Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani]] - Volume 34''. [[Treccani]].</ref>
